On Tuesday, the CAR's fourth-largest town, Bambari, 380 kilometres northeast of Bangui, was overrun but security forces backed by UN peacekeepers regained control the following day.
On Sunday, polling stations in Bambari remained closed in the morning because of gunfire from armed groups, according to Jeannot Nguernendji, president of the local peace committee.
Legitimacy concerns
The mineral-rich but poverty-stricken CAR has been unstable since independence 60 years ago.
Thousands of people have died since a civil war erupted in 2013 and more than a quarter of the population of 4.9 million have fled their homes. Of these, 675,000 are refugees in neighbouring countries and cannot vote.
Even though bloodshed has receded in intensity over the last two years, violence remains chronic. Militia groups hold sway over two-thirds of the territory.
Experts and opposition figures have already asked what legitimacy the president and 140 MPs to be elected will have, given the obstacles to holding a free vote. The polls take place after a week of turbulence, marked by accusations of an attempted coup. An overview of its recent history ahead of the country's presidential election this weekend. He was found in a thicket about three kilometres away from Aberdare Country Club. FAO says swarms in Ethiopia, Somalia and Tanzania threaten Kenya’s food security. Nyeri's Serene Haven, which is set to open in January, already has 32 students confirmed to enroll.